Sangguniang Kabataan Reform Act of 2015
The Sangguniang Kabataan (SK) Reform Act of 2015, officially known as Republic Act No. 10742, is a Philippine law enacted to revitalize youth participation in governance. It restructured the SK system to promote accountability, transparency, and genuine youth empowerment in local government.

Key Facts
Full Title: Republic Act No. 10742

Signed Into Law: January 15, 2016

Principal Author: Senator Ferdinand Marcos Jr. (among others)

Implementing Agency: Department of the Interior and Local Government (DILG) and National Youth Commission (NYC)

Focus: Youth representation and governance reform

Background and Purpose
The law was passed to address persistent criticisms of the old SK system, which was often marred by political patronage and lack of capacity. It sought to create a more transparent and effective mechanism for involving young people in local governance, policymaking, and community development. It also aligned youth participation with broader good-governance reforms.

Major Reforms Introduced
Key reforms include raising the age qualification for SK officials from 15–17 to 18–24 years old, introducing mandatory training on governance and leadership, and requiring the creation of a Comprehensive Barangay Youth Development Plan. It also introduced an anti-political dynasty provision, barring relatives within the second civil degree of local officials from running.

Structure and Responsibilities
Under the law, each barangay maintains an SK Chairperson and a council of seven members. They formulate policies, implement youth programs, and coordinate with the barangay council. Funding is provided through the 10% allocation of the barangay’s general fund, ensuring resources for youth development initiatives.

Accountability and Oversight
The act emphasizes fiscal transparency, mandating annual financial reports and open consultations with youth constituents. It also established a Local Youth Development Council (LYDC) at municipal and city levels to harmonize programs and monitor SK performance, thereby institutionalizing accountability mechanisms.

Impact and Implementation
The SK Reform Act marked the first comprehensive overhaul of the youth council since its establishment in 1975. It reintroduced youth elections in 2018 after a five-year suspension and continues to shape youth leadership and civic engagement across the Philippines.